<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="hw1-intro-to-data" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Homework 1</title>

  <subsection xml:id="hw1-terminology">
    <title>Terminology</title>
      <p>
        The following terminology will be used throughout the course: 
      </p> 
      <definition xml:id="def-population">
        <title>Population</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A collection of individuals (not necessarily people) that share one or more common characteristics.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        In statistics, this is the entire group of individuals for which information is being gathered or studied. Information that describes the entire population is called <term>descriptive statistics</term>
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-sample">
        <title>Sample</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A subset of the population.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        In statistics, it is often neither feasible nor desirable to gather information about the entire population, so information is gathered on part of the population being studied. <term>Inferential statistics</term> describes when information gathered about the sample is used to say something about the population.
      </p>
      <example xml:id = "w1-popsample-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the total viewers of a television show. The following are examples of samples of this population: viewers in the United States; viewers between the ages 18 and 35; male-identifying viewers.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>

      <definition xml:id="def-variable">
        <title>Variable</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A quantity or quality of the population that varies among individuals.    
          </p>
          <p>
            A <term>quantitative variable</term> is one which can be measured and which produces a numerical value. A <term>qualitative variable</term> or <term>categorical variable</term> is one which produces a description of the population.
          </p>
          <p>
            <term>Data</term> are the values of variables.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <note>
        <p>
          Categorical variables can sometimes have numerical representations, if they are used to categorize individuals in the population. 
        </p>
      </note>
      <definition xml:id="def-parameter">
        <title>Parameter</title>    
        <statement>
          <p>
            A value found by looking at the entire population.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-statistic">
        <title>Statistic</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A value found by looking at a sample of the population.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example xml:id="w1-parameterstatistic-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In a recent survey, 1000 Oklahomans were polled on their opinion about a federal law requiring background checks for all gun purchases. 88% would support the law. 
          </p>
          <p>
            In this example, 88% represents a statistic because the 1000 people were chosen from the population of Oklahoma; it's not feasible to ask the entire population, so a subset (1000 people) were asked. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>

      <example xml:id="w1-parameterstatistic-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A construction foreman asked his workers about their preferences for lunch. 45% wanted pizza, 20% wanted Mexican, 25% wanted Italian, and 10% wanted salad. 
          </p>
          <p>
            In this example, each percentage represents a parameter, not a statistic. As opposed to <xref ref="w1-parameterstatistic-1"/>, it is possible to get information from all individuals on the worksite; this is why the values represent parameters rather than statistics.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <exercise xml:id="hw1-check-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Identify the population, sample, parameter, sample, variable, and data in the situation below.
          </p>
          <p>
            A restaurant chain wants to determine the amount of average amount of money that University of Oklahoma students spend at its restaurants in each month. To begin answering this question, they ask 100 students their opinions; three students gave responses of $0, $100, and $25, respectively.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The population is "students at the University of Oklahoma".
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The sample is the 100 students asked their opinions.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The parameter is the monthly average of money spent at the restaurant chain.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The statistic is the monthly average of money spent by the 100 students.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The variable is the amount of money spent by the students at the restaurant group.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Note: The variable is distinct from the parameter, because the parameter is the <alert>average</alert> amount spent, not the <alert>total</alert> amount spent.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The data are the dollar amounts given by the three students: $0, $100, and $50.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="hw1-variables">
    <title>Types of Variables</title>
      <example xml:id="hw1-variables-ex1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Recall that <xref ref="def-variable"/> introduced <term>quantitative</term> and <term>qualitative</term> variables (also called <term>categorical</term> variables). 
          </p>
          <p>
            Examples of quantitative variables describing OCCC students are: height, weight, age, GPA, and hours taken
          </p>
          <p>
            Examples of qualitative variables describing OCCC students are: gender, race, classification (e.g. freshman, sophomore), hair color, phone number, ZIP code, and letter grade in a course.
          </p>
        </statement>
        
      </example>
      <note>
        <p>
          Even though phone number and ZIP code display numbers, they are not numerical: they are classifying students by an identifier. These numbers are not measurements and cannot be used in further calculations (does the average of a phone number make sense?)
        </p>
      </note>
      <definition xml:id="def-discrete-cts-variable">
        <title>Discrete/Continuous Variable</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <alert>quantitative variable</alert> is a <term>discrete variable</term> if it cannot take on any value between the minimum and maximum value of the variable being studied. The number of values that can be taken by the variable is clearly defined or can be counted. 
          </p>
          <p>
            A <alert>quantitative variable</alert> is a <term>continuous variable</term> if it can take on any value between the minimum and maximum value of the variable being studied.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example xml:id="hw1-discrete-cts-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The following are examples of discrete variables: age, shoe size, number of siblings, number of gas stations in a city. 
          </p>
          <p>
            The following are examples of continuous variables: height, weight, GPA, time, volume, pressure
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <exercise xml:id="hw1-discrete-cts-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Is the number of credit hours taken by an OCCC student this semester a discrete or continuous variable?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            It is a discrete variable because it's impossible to take anything other than a whole number of hours; taking 13.25 hours is impossible. Since you cannot take on any value between the minimum and maximum (0 and 21 hours), this is a discrete variable.
          </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
      <assemblage xml:id="hw1-callout-1">
        <title>Distinguishing Between Continuous and Discrete Variables</title>
        <p>
          Continuous variables are types of variables that we can get more and more precise measurements from. The precision is only limited by the device we are using to measure it. For example, someone's weight could be 182.126 pounds and that number makes perfect sense. And if we had a better scale, we could get an even more precise measurement.  For a discrete variable, the variable can only take on a certain number of values- not all values would make sense- like shoe size. 12.5 would make sense but a value like 12.456 would not. There is only a discrete (limited/countable) number of values that a discrete variable could have. Things that we are measuring scientifically tend to be continuous variables because the precision of measurement is only determined by the instrument doing the measuring.  
        </p>
      </assemblage>
      <definition xml:id="def-nominal-ordinal">
        <title>Nominal/Ordinal Variable</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <alert>qualitative variable</alert> is a <term>nominal variable</term> if there is no natural ordering of the variables.
          </p>
          <p>
            A <alert>qualitative variable</alert> is an <term>ordinal variable</term> if there is a natural ordering of the variables.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example xml:id="hw1-nominal-ordinal-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Examples of nominal variables include: gender, race, hair color, ZIP code
          </p>
          <p>
            Examples of ordinal variables include: year classification (e.g. freshman, sophomore), military rank, letter grade in a course.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <exercise xml:id="hw1-nominal-ordinal-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine whether the given variable is nominal or ordinal:
          </p>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Brand of laptop 
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Drink size at a fast food restaurant
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Size (in page count) of statistics textbooks
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Statistics textbooks used
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Nominal, because there is no natural ordering to the variables (is <c>Dell</c> larger or smaller than <c>Apple</c>?)
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Ordinal, because there is a natural ordering (small is smaller than medium, which is smaller than large)
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Ordinal, because there is a natural ordering (books with fewer page numbers are smaller than those with larger page numbers)
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Nominal, because there is no natural ordering to the variables (<c>Diez</c> is not larger or smaller than <c>Illowsky</c> or <c>Triola</c>)
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="hw1-sampling">
    <title>Sampling Methods</title>
    <p>
      Most populations we study or work with within Statistics are of enormous size: think of the population of all U.S. households or the population of all eligible voters in the U.S. These populations contains tens of millions of individual data points, so it is not feasible (in terms of time, cost, etc.) to study the whole population directly. For populations where it is not desirable to study each individual from a population, we choose a representative sample. 
    </p>

    <assemblage xml:id="hw1-sampling-validmethods-defs">
      <title>List of Valid Sampling Methods</title>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Simple Random Sampling</term>: We randomly choose the desired number of individuals out of the entire population of individuals. This method is valid because it allows all individuals an equal chance to be picked as part of a sample.
            </p>
            <p>
              Simple random sampling is the most basic and common method for choosing a valid statistical sample out of a population
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Stratified Random Sampling</term>: This is a more advanced version of random sampling. We still choose a random sample; however, we also stratify it to closely match with the demographics of the population we choose our sample from. All medical and healthcare-related studies are conducted using this sampling method.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Cluster Sampling</term>: Cluster sampling occurs when there are 'natural' groupings evident in a population. It is often used in marketing research. In this technique, the total population is divided into these groups (called clusters) and a sample of the groups is selected.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Systematic Sampling</term>: Sample members from a larger population are selected according to a random starting point and a fixed, periodic interval. This is often used when doing quality control for a particular product.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </assemblage>
    <example xml:id="hw1-sampling-validmethods-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Simple Random Sampling</alert>: Drawing names from a hat is an example of simple random sampling - everyone from the population is in the hat and has an equal opportunity to be chosen for the sample.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Stratified Random Sampling</alert>: Suppose we want to poll a sample of eligible voters to find out how they plan to vote in an upcoming election. In this population, 44% of voters are registered as Democrat, 42% as Republican, and 12% as independent. The stratified random sample we use for this poll should also reflect these percentages, so around 42% of all individuals should be chosen from the pool of all eligible Republican voters, 44% from all Democratic voters, and 12% from all independent voters.
              </p>
            </li>        
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Cluster Sampling</alert>: Suppose that Major League Baseball decides to do random drug testing during the season. They can do a cluster sampling by considering each division as one large cluster, and randomly choosing one or more divisions. Suppose the division 'AL East' is chosen; this means that all members of the AL East (Yankees, Orioles, Red Sox, Rays) would be randomly tested.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Systematic Sampling</alert>: A soda pop company wants to make sure they have a consistent product so they systematically take every 100th can off the assembly line to get tested for consistency.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <exercise xml:id="hw1-sampling-validmethods-2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Suppose a population is 60% male and 40% female. If we want the final sample to match the percentages in the population, are we using simple random, stratified random, cluster, or systematic sampling?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                How many individuals should be chosen from the male population?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                How many individuals should be chosen from the female population?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Stratified random sampling.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                6 males, because 6/10 = 60%. The percentage of males in the sample should match the percentage of males in the population in stratified random sampling.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                4 females, because 4/10 = 40%. The percentage of females in the sample should match the percentage of females in the population in stratified random sampling.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="hw1-sampling-validmethods-3">
      <statement>
        <p>
          It has been speculated that the apples from an orchard of apple trees in Maine has more health benefits than apples found elsewhere.  A group of scientists decide to conduct a study on the apples in the orchard to test the validity of the speculation.
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                What is the population in this study?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Scientists don't want to harvest all the apples in the orchard so they choose to use a sample of 100 apples instead.  Determine the type of sampling that the scientist do in each of the following scenarios.    
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Scientists choose 5 apples from every three trees in the orchard until they have gotten all 100 apples for their sample.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Scientists randomly pick 30 green apples, 50 red apples, and 20 yellow apples because 30% of the apples in the orchard are believed to be green apples, 50% of the apples in orchard have red apples, and 20% of the trees have yellow apples.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Scientists decide to pick all 100 apples from 3 trees in the orchard- a tree having red apples, a tree having yellow apples, and a tree having green apples.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                All apples in the orchard.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Simple random sample.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Systematic sample.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Stratified random sample.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Cluster sample.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <assemblage xml:id="hw1-sampling-invalidmethods-defs">
      <title>List of Invalid Sampling Methods</title>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Voluntary-response Sampling</term>: This occurs when the members of the sample choose to be part of the sample.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Non-response Sampling</term>: This occurs when a sample is not large enough to represent a population.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Sample of Convenience</term>: This occurs when the sample is chosen from convenient data points to the researcher.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </assemblage>
    <example xml:id="hw1-sampling-invalidmethods-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A radio talk show in Oklahoma City asks people to chime in on who they think the best point guard in the NBA is.
        </p>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Voluntary-response Sampling</alert>:                 
                  The people that call in will feel very passionate about whom they feel is the best and the fact they are listening to a particular radio station might indicate that they will all have similar views.  It is very unlikely that this small sample calling into the radio station will feel the same way as the general population unless everyone in Oklahoma City listens to this radio station and they are all passionate about basketball. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Non-reponse Sampling</alert>: If 5 people call in to the station and all say that Shai Gilgeous-Alexander is the best point guard, this is not as convincing as if 500 people called in and declared Shai the best point guard. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <alert>Sample of Convenience</alert>: If the radio station claims that Shai Gilgeous-Alexander is the best point guard in the NBA based on the views of its callers, this is a sample of convenience because the sample (conveniently drawn from nearby listeners) is not representative of the entire population of NBA fans.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="hw1-sampling-invalidmethods-2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Sometimes a sample of convenience is ok.
        </p>
        <p>
          A farmer wants to sell his newly harvested apples to a grocery store.  In the back of his truck the farmer has his apples in numerous crates.  The grocery store manager only examines the apples in the top of each crate (whether than checking the bottom) when deciding whether or not to buy the apples.  A sample of convenience is ok when it can be used to represent the entire population.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="hw1-studies-experiments">
    <title>Observational Studies and Experiments</title>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-studies">
      <title>Statistical Studies</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>statistical study</term> is the way that statisticians and researchers gather information about the individuals from a population.
        </p>
        <p>
          Studies can either take the design of an <term>observational study</term> or an <term>experiment</term> depending on the role of the researcher, the person conducting the study.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <assemblage xml:id="hw1-studies-observational">
      <title>Observational Study</title>
      <p>
        In an <term>observational study</term>, the researcher only gathers information about a population through observation.
      </p>
      <p>
        If the purpose of the observational study is to compare groups within the population, the researcher will not assign individuals from the population into the groups.  The individuals either naturally fall within the groups or they have chosen to be in a group for themselves.
      </p>
      <p>
        In an observational study the researcher does not manipulate or influence the behaviors of the population in any way.
      </p>
    </assemblage>
    <example xml:id="hw1-studies-observational-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Observational studies have linked smoking to poorer health outcomes. Researchers would follow smokers and non-smokers and record the health differences between the two groups.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is an observational study because at no point did the researcher influence the behaviors of the individuals that they were observing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Because of this lack of control for behaviors such as diet and exercise, researchers could only conclude that it was very likely that smoking had an adverse effect on one's health.  Also the researchers could not say that smoking was the direct cause of bad health.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <note>
      <p>
        Observational studies can usually show <alert>correlation</alert> (variables are related in some way) but not <alert>causation</alert>, where one variable is the direct cause of another (e.g. smoking is the direct cause of bad health).
      </p>
    </note>
    <assemblage xml:id="hw1-studies-experiments-experiments">
      <title>Experiments</title>
      <p>
        In an <term>experiment</term>, the researcher manipulates the population in some manner.
      </p>
      <p>
        One way that the researcher does this is by assigning individuals from the population into groups: <term>experiment</term>, which receives the experimental treatment, and <term>control</term>, which does not receive the experimental treatment.
      </p>
      <p>
        Individuals do not choose for themselves which group they will be a part of.  The researcher does this so that they can determine if administrating a treatment to one of the groups will cause a response that does not happen in the group that did not receive the treatment.
      </p>    
      <p>
        Unlike an observational study, the researcher in an experiment can influence the behaviors of subjects to control for lurking variables.
      </p>
    </assemblage>
    <example xml:id="hw1-studies-experiments-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider a hypothetical experiment designed to determine whether or not smoking <alert>causes</alert> bad health.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the experiment group, researchers randomly choose a sample of people from the population and give them a treatment. In this experiment, the individuals or subjects in this group would be asked to smoke (which would be highly unethical).
        </p>
        <p>
          For the control group, researchers would randomly choose a sample of people from the population that will be told not to smoke.
        </p>
        <p>
          Researchers would then try to control for lurking variables by controlling the behaviors of the two groups. For example, they might give both groups the same diet, exercise plan, require the same amount of sleep, etc. 
        </p>
        <p>
          In some experiments, researchers would also control for the <term>placebo effect</term>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="def-placeboeffect">
      <title>Placebo Effect</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>placebo effect</term> occurs when people think they are receiving a treatment when in actuality they are not. The mere thought of receiving the treatment in some individuals is enough to cause an effect.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <assemblage xml:id="hw1-studies-experiment-terminology">
      <title>Terminology Associated with an Experiment</title>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Sample</term>: If not specified it always means a simple random sample of individuals chosen from the population.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Subject</term>: An individual chosen at random from a population for an experiment.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Explanatory Variable</term>: A quantity used to measure the outcome of an experiment.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Response Variable</term>: A quantity used to measure the outcome of an experiment.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Treatment</term>: A combination of one or more explanatory factors in an experiment.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Double-Blind Experiment</term>: An experiment where neither the researcher nor the subjects know which group (control or experimental) they are in.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Lurking Variables</term>: Variables that have an influence on the response variable that are not accounted for in the study.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </assemblage>
    <exercise xml:id="hw1-studies-experiments-2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="hw1-studies-experiments-1"/>, determine the explanatory variable, response variable, and treatment for the experiment.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The explanatory variable is 'whether or not the subject smokes', the response variable is 'the various health outcomes', and the treatment is 'giving cigarettes to the individuals in the experimental group'.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="hw1-studies-experiments-3">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A fitness instructor wants to determine the effect that fitness classes have on body fat composition. Determine which is an observational study and which is a randomized experiment.
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The fitness instructor measures the body fat composition of the participants of the 4 different classes that have already begun: yoga, Zumba, pilates, and Tae Bo. She later takes the body fat composition of each participant the last week of class to see which class made the largest improvement.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                She measures the body fat composition of 100 fitness class participants and then she randomly assigns the participants to yoga, Zumba, pilates, and Tae Bo. She later takes the body fat composition of each participant the last week of class to see which class made the largest improvement.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                This is an observational study because the classes have already started. This implies that the participants chose for themselves which class(es) they would be in. The fitness instructor is not assigning treatment to the participants, which is essential for a randomized experiments.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                This is a randomized experiment because the fitness instructor is randomly assigning the treatment to participants.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="hw1-studies-experiments-4">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A soda pop company wants to measure the satisfaction level of two of its products, brand X and brand Y to determine which to promote. Which of the following describes an observational study and which describes an experiment?
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The company decides to poll 50 people that had already tried brand X and and 50 people that had already tried brand Y about their satisfaction level.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The company randomly chooses 100 people, 50 of which are assigned to brand X, and 50 to brand Y. After trying the brands, those chosen for the study were asked their satisfaction level.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                This is an observational study because those polled had already tried brand X and brand Y on their own.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                This is a randomized experiment because the company assigns people to try either brand X or brand Y.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
</section>